<Author>Waterwise
<Content>Adequate... We spent 5 nights at the Fairmont. We were upgraded from a 鈥楧eluxe鈥?room to an 鈥楨xecutive鈥?Room on the 22nd Floor. This entitled us to enjoy the 鈥楨xecutive Club鈥? a lounge offering all-day snacks and free cocktails in the evening- no kids allowed. We have 2 young ones so no value to us. There is also a small gym up there for 鈥楨xecutive鈥?guests. The room was fine- modern d茅cor, surround sound, flat screen TV, electric curtains, etc.. Nice spacious modern bathroom, king-size shower. We think it a waste to have all linen changed every day but there is really no option but to have ones towels replaced every day as nowhere to hang them up, simply a large basket to throw them in! We had booked a room with king-size bed (and cot) but were given 2 doubles. Best they could do was push doubles together and make up bed with king-size linen. Coffee/tea making facilities- there is a smart expresso machine. If, like us, you drink tea, take your tea bags with you. The 2 provided don鈥檛 go far! The cups are designed for an expresso from the coffee maker so you could just about use one bag for 2 cups (there is all-day coffee and tea from the 鈥楨xecutive Club鈥?(if you don鈥檛 have kids!)). With our air con set to its lowest speed and highest temperature (30degC) we were freezing. The 鈥榚ngineer鈥?was assigned to fix this. The following night with the air con set at its highest speed and lowest temperature (20degC) we were in a sauna bath. The following day the 鈥榚ngineer鈥?returned- we then returned to the arctic and simply decided to 鈥榬ug-up鈥? At least we could open the door on to the little balcony- something you cannot often do in high-rise hotels. Our package included breakfast. Breakfast is standard hotel buffet style. Seems like hotels try to outdo each other for the most obscure dishes for breakfast- you look at half this stuff and wonder just WHO would want THAT for breakfast. If you came down from Mars there鈥檇 be something you鈥檇 like. No particular reflection on this hotel in particular (there almost ALL the same) but is anyone else out there sick of the breakfast offering of leather for bacon and sausages that look more like they鈥檙e boiled than grilled or fried? Whilst I鈥檓 about it has anyone ever met one of those motorised toaster machines that makes a piece of toast (as opposed to warmed bread) in one 鈥榩ass鈥? Singapore hotels cater for a very cosmopolitan clientele including many UK/American  Australasian clients. Amongst the okra sambal, the sio mai, chicken curry, steamed pork buns, chick pea curry and miso soup there was nothing as simple as baked beans in tomato sauce. On one morning only were there some soggy little hash browns. Amongst the salads, dozens of cold meats and cheeses and fruits I had never even seen before there were no mushrooms saut茅ed, grilled or cooked by any means whatsoever. Take the tea鈥?the coffee is well and truly stewed.The hotel pool on the 8th floor is great and good for kids including our littlies. There is a separate kids鈥?pool.The concierge was helpful  forthcoming on tourist info except when we sought info on the harbour cruise. He sent us off to the Esplanade (20 minute walk) which is where he had advised the boats left from. With 2 little kids in tow we trudged the length of the Esplanade. We had another 20 minute walk to the 鈥榤erlion鈥?fountain to find where the boats actually DO leave from.Whilst the room was tidy and new some parts of the hotel look a little jaded. The furniture in the 鈥榣ounge鈥?off reception are reminiscent of grandad鈥檚 favourite old chair you wish he鈥檇 get rid of.One benefit of staying here is that the hotel is part of Raffles Square (with THE Raffles across the road) which is full of ritzy stores and restaurants aplenty). Reception is friendly and helpful, the service is generally very attentive.The hotel is unremarkable, a not untypical modern and rather soulless Singapore Hotel-not much not to criticise it for, not much to recommend it for either. 
